	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Developing new partnerships for movement up the coffee value chain</h1>

			
			<h4>
												09 September 2012
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>According to press reports, while currently Kenya ‘sells most of its coffee to Europe’, Chinese partners are being sought for joint ventures in coffee processing, as part of a Kenyan strategy to shift away from traditional markets to trade with faster growing markets in Asia and Africa. The Coffee Board of Kenya is looking for partners to help expand ‘local processing and packaging capacity to improve export of processed coffee to the emerging foreign coffee markets’. It is considered that this would help insulate Kenya producers from the price volatility being experienced on global coffee bean markets. At present, ‘access to appropriate machinery is one of the major challenges facing Kenya enterprises… limiting most of the local business people to being export brokers of the raw produce’. Linking up with Chinese investors is seen as one means of turning Kenya into a global coffee hub, particularly as it would help access the rapidly expanding Chinese coffee market. To date, ‘Kenya does not have a strong history of coffee trade with China, with first major coffee exports to the country having started in 2007’.</p><p>As part of this broader strategy, government is rolling out ‘plans to promote growing of robusta coffee in non-traditional coffee growing areas’, so as to generate volumes of robusta coffee sufficient to justify investments in processing of instant coffee, demand for which is seen as growing across the world.</p><p>Meanwhile, the Coffee Research Foundation has identified new potential areas for coffee production in response to climate change and changes in land use in peri-urban areas.</p><p>In neighbouring Tanzania, however, according to press reports ‘the long-term existence of the Tanzanian coffee sector is threatened as the overall volume of production has become so low that roasters do not consider it anymore as a potential ingredient to their blends’.</p><p>This followed reports in June 2012 of growing interest in Rwandan coffee from Japanese coffee buyers, who currently import ‘between three and five tonnes of speciality coffee per year’. To date, ‘Japanese importers have been buying Rwandan coffee through European importers or from Kenya.’ However, the plan now is to ‘ship the commodity directly from the country’, although ‘Japanese importers are challenged by inland transportation hitches from Rwanda, which is very expensive compared to Tanzania and Kenya.’&nbsp;</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>Xinhua, ‘Kenya turns to China in a bid to process her own coffee’, 12 July 2012</p><p>
<a href="http://allafrica.com/stories/201207121006.html" target="_self">http://allafrica.com/stories/201207121006.html</a></p><p>The Star, ‘South Rift new coffee frontier, say researchers’, 25 June 2012</p><p>
<a href="http://allafrica.com/stories/201206260136.html" target="_self">http://allafrica.com/stories/201206260136.html</a></p><p>Tanzania Daily News, ‘Amended strategy to transform coffee industry', 18 June 2012</p><p>
<a href="http://allafrica.com/stories/201206180089.html" target="_self">http://allafrica.com/stories/201206180089.html</a></p><p>New Times (Rwanda), ‘Japanese coffee cuppers commend nation's coffee’, 7 June 2012</p><p>
<a href="http://allafrica.com/stories/201206070915.html" target="_self">http://allafrica.com/stories/201206070915.html</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>How to capitalise on growing consumer demand in Asia and Africa in order to transform the structural engagement of ACP agro-food sectors with the global economy is currently a critical challenge, particularly given the scale of the economic downturn in parts of the EU. While in the short term the targeting of Chinese investors is primarily intended to overcome constraints posed by the high costs of loan financing in East Africa (with China being seen as a potential source of cheap financing for the development of value-added processing), the identification of Asian joint venture partners potentially offers an important vehicle for redefining the Kenyan coffee sector’s engagement with the global economy, as it would provide direct access to one of the fastest growing markets for coffee.</p><p>However, given the size of the Chinese market, ensuring an expansion in the volume of coffee production would appear to be essential if such a strategy is to be successful and Kenya is to turn itself into a global hub for coffee processing.</p><p>This would appear to offer considerable potential for regional cooperation, particularly in view of the difficulties currently faced in Tanzania. However, as the experience in Rwanda suggests, this will require getting to grips with issues that undermine the efficient functioning of coffee supply chains (including logistical constraints on exports).</p><p>While the emergence of Kenyan roasters, blenders and processors could offer a new outlet for Tanzanian and other regional coffee production, it could also offer scope for the development of joint marketing strategies for single-origin and other premium label coffees similar to those adopted in the Caribbean rum sector under the ‘Authentic Caribbean Rum’ quality label. In the Caribbean, common standards were developed that allowed collective market repositioning of quality-differentiated rums (serving similar market components to those for single malt whisky producers), while allowing individual companies to negotiate their own corporate marketing arrangements. Similar joint initiatives in the East African coffee sector could greatly reduce the costs and improve the efficiency of efforts to reposition East African coffee within evolving global coffee markets.</p>
		</div>
		
